N1  - Funding text 1: The hosting costs for HUBzero have increased in the past ten years resulting in a significant expense to maintain an individual hub for the entire project period which often ranges from 3 years to 5 years. Each of the four projects discussed, struggled to pay the hosting costs each year prior to merging on MyGeoHub. In the past few years, the driNET project’s funding has expired, but the data and online tools developed by the project are still available to the community at no cost to the project. Similarly, the Geoshare project’s original funding expired after two years. With the hub continuously running, the PI of the Geoshare project could demonstrate the prior work to several funding agencies and successfully secured follow-up funding from USDA, Purdue Research Park, and the Mellon Grant Foundation subsequently.
N1  - Funding text 2: The Cyverse [ 21 ], HydroShare, CyberGIS [ 22 ] and Galaxy [ 23 ] gateway providers fall under the first category; providing domain-specific tools and workflow capabilities for individual science domains. They typically include the most popular tools from their scientific domain with dedicated gateway developers maintaining and adding such tools. While Cyverse allows users to contribute their own tools, this involves converting them into Docker containers to be used in Cyverse’s Discovery Environment (DE) data management system or in Cyverse’s Atmosphere VMs. Typical use-cases involve individual researchers or groups managing their data and experiments in the central Cyverse gateway with small amounts of data storage or computation needs being supported free-of-cost. Cyverse requires such research results to be either published or retrieved with an associated data recovery fee. Larger resource demands are supported either by obtaining a letter of support from Cyverse for inclusion in funding proposals or by simply paying for usage.
